    <!-- Publications Section -->
    <section id="publications" class="py-20 bg-gray-50 section-bg dark:bg-gray-900">
        <div class="container mx-auto px-6 section-content">
            <div class="text-center mb-16" data-aos="fade-up">
                <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-textlight">Creative Corner</h2>
                <div class="w-20 h-1 bg-gradient-to-r from-primary to-secondary mx-auto mt-4 rounded-full"></div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto">
                <div class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm border border-gray-100 overflow-hidden card-hover dark:bg-gray-800 dark:border-gray-700" data-aos="flip-up">
                    <div class="p-8">
                        <div class="space-y-8">
                            <div class="flex flex-col md:flex-row gap-6 pb-8 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-700">
                                <div class="md:w-1/4">
                                    <div class="bg-gray-100 rounded-lg overflow-hidden shadow-sm dark:bg-gray-700">
                                        <img src="https://www.canva.com/design/DAGmOdYx_R0/p9ZzQLtuiGfLfKDnzhqw-w/edit"
                                             alt="Unshakan:The Story Of resilience" class="w-full h-auto object-cover object-top transition-transform duration-500 hover:scale-105">
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                                <div class="md:w-3/4">
                                    <h4 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2 dark:text-textlight">Unshaken: The Story of Resilience</h4>
                                    <div class="flex items-center gap-4 mb-4">
                                        <div class="flex items-center gap-2">
                                            <div class="w-5 h-5 flex items-center justify-center text-primary">
                                                <i class="ri-calendar-line"></i>
                                            </div>
                                            <span class="text-gray-600 text-sm dark:text-gray-400">May 2025</span>
                                        </div>
                                        <div class="flex items-center gap-2">
                                            <div class="w-5 h-5 flex items-center justify-center text-primary">
                                                <i class="ri-book-open-line"></i>
                                            </div>
                                            <span class="text-gray-600 text-sm dark:text-gray-400">Short Story</span>
                                        </div>
                                    </div>
                                    <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4 dark:text-gray-400">
                                        <span class="short-text">Aarohi's life was that of chaos and noise—hands raised in anger; voices as weapons; love that created a battleground versus a sanctuary. She learned to be strong, to work hard, and to be the best at everything; because if she was perfect, perhaps she would receive love.
                                        When people say that the world does not return kindness in the way that we want it to—there was no falsehood in that statement. She had poured so much of herself into the people in her life, and no one truly saw her. And just as she was finally ready to immerse herself in success, life decided to challenge her one last time. The night before her final interview, the past came crashing in—doubt, fear, overwhelm, trauma.
                                        </span>
                                        <span class="long-text" style="display: none;">She could have fallen apart. She almost did.
                                        And then she realized that she would never again be a victim of whatever broke her. She walked into that interview and put everything on the line. She walked into that interview and left everything on the table.
                                        Many years later, she now sits at the head of the table—as CEO—with admiration and respect, with love. But the truth is, she was always more than enough. Long before there were titles—validation—recognition—she had already won.
                                        Success isn't about proving the world wrong, it is about knowing your worth when no one else does.
                                        </span>
                                    </p>
                                    <button class="read-more text-primary hover:text-primary-dark transition-colors flex items-center gap-1 animated-underline">
                                        Read More
                                        <i class="ri-arrow-right-line"></i>
                                    </button>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                            
                            <div class="flex flex-col md:flex-row gap-6 pb-8 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-700">
                                <div class="md:w-1/4">
                                    <div class="bg-gray-100 rounded-lg overflow-hidden shadow-sm dark:bg-gray-700">
                                        <img src="https://www.canva.com/design/DAGmBmE9GkU/BzFen0u4B1L2iCo1de8icg/edit"
                                             alt="Mental Health" class="w-full h-auto object-cover object-top transition-transform duration-500 hover:scale-105">
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                                <div class="md:w-3/4">
                                    <h4 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2 dark:text-textlight">Mental Health in Digital Age: Challenges and Solutions</h4>
                                    <div class="flex items-center gap-4 mb-4">
                                        <div class="flex items-center gap-2">
                                            <div class="w-5 h-5 flex items-center justify-center text-primary">
                                                <i class="ri-calendar-line"></i>
                                            </div>
                                            <span class="text-gray-600 text-sm dark:text-gray-400">March 2025</span>
                                        </div>
                                        <div class="flex items-center gap-2">
                                            <div class="w-5 h-5 flex items-center justify-center text-primary">
                                                <i class="ri-article-line"></i>
                                            </div>
                                            <span class="text-gray-600 text-sm dark:text-gray-400">Article</span>
                                        </div>
                                    </div>
                                    <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4 dark:text-gray-400">
                                        <span class="short-text">In today's digital world, technology has become an integral part of our lives. From social media platforms to instant messaging, digital tools have completely transformed how we communicate, work, and even unwind. However, with these benefits comes a growing concern: the impact of the digital era on our mental health.
                                        <br><br>
                                        <strong>The Hidden Challenges</strong><br>
                                        1. Culture of comparison: Social media tends to present the highlight reels, rather than the bts. Ongoing exposure can damage self-esteem and feed anxiety.<br>
                                        2. Burnout digital: Nonstop notifications, screen time, and multitasking leave us eye fatigue and mentally and emotionally drained.<br>
                                        3. Cyberbullying & toxicity online: The incognito status of the internet gives rise to negativity and harassment, particularly among young people.<br>
                                        4. Isolation in an interconnected world: Virtual connections can't always substitute actual human interaction and might lead to feelings of loneliness and isolation.
                                        <br><br>
                                        <strong>The Way Out</strong><br>
                                        1. Digital boundaries: Small changes—screen limits, focus time, social media breaks—can make a big difference.<br>
                                        </span>
                                        <span class="long-text" style="display: none;">2. Mindful consumption: Follow content that uplifts, educates, and inspires. Unfollow what drains you.<br>
                                        3. Use tech for good: Teletherapy apps, meditation tools, and support communities are just a few clicks away.<br>
                                        4. Stand up & support one another: Let's make talking about mental health a norm and be there for one another—online & offline.
                                        <br><br>
                                        Are we truly coping with the pace of digital life—or are we silently crumbling under it?
                                        Your mental health matters more than your screen stats.
                                        If this relates with you, or you have a story to share, DM me—I'd love to hear your take. Let's keep the dialogue going.
                                        </span>
                                    </p>
                                    <button class="read-more text-primary hover:text-primary-dark transition-colors flex items-center gap-1 animated-underline">
                                        Read More
                                        <i class="ri-arrow-right-line"></i>
                                    </button>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                            
                            <div class="flex flex-col md:flex-row gap-6">
                                <div class="md:w-1/4">
                                    <div class="bg-gray-100 rounded-lg overflow-hidden shadow-sm dark:bg-gray-700">
                                        <img src="https://www.google.com/url?sa=i&url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.thestatesman.com%2Ffeatures%2Finternational-womens-day-in-historical-perspective-1503160521.html&psig=AOvVaw3vCBZ4PTKsKRDjX_A35gjJ&ust=1746283697857000&source=images&cd=vfe&opi=89978449&ved=0CBQQjRxqFwoTCLiwlfiDhY0DFQAAAAAdAAAAABAQ"
                                             alt="Women Leadership" class="w-full h-auto object-cover object-top transition-transform duration-500 hover:scale-105">
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                                <div class="md:w-3/4">
                                    <h4 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2 dark:text-textlight">Balancing Roles: The 'Perfect Daughter' and an Emerging Leader</h4>
                                    <div class="flex items-center gap-4 mb-4">
                                        <div class="flex items-center gap-2">
                                            <div class="w-5 h-5 flex items-center justify-center text-primary">
                                                <i class="ri-calendar-line"></i>
                                            </div>
                                            <span class="text-gray-600 text-sm dark:text-gray-400">March 2025</span>
                                        </div>
                                        <div class="flex items-center gap-2">
                                            <div class="w-5 h-5 flex items-center justify-center text-primary">
                                                <i class="ri-article-line"></i>
                                            </div>
                                            <span class="text-gray-600 text-sm dark:text-gray-400">Article</span>
                                        </div>
                                    </div>
                                    <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4 dark:text-gray-400">
                                        <span class="short-text">Coming from a nuclear family, most daughters are trained to be perfect. We are supposed to be ambitious and humble, independent and family-centric, and strong and caring. Juggling all this while moving into leadership positions in our professional lives often feels like walking a tightrope.
                                        <br><br>
                                        <strong>The Weight of Expectations—"Perfect Daughter"</strong><br>
                                        Daughters in most cultures bear the unseen but weighty burden of family expectations. From academic achievement and career success to maintaining tradition and family values, the responsibility to "do it all" is staggering. Though these expectations are usually based on love, they can become restrictive—especially as we see our mothers work through similar roles, putting personal and professional ambitions aside in the process.
                                        <br><br>
                                        <strong>Navigating Leadership as a Woman</strong><br>
                                        Leadership is tough enough without extra scrutiny. Confidence, risk-taking, and decisive action—essential qualities of great leaders—sometimes conflict with the idealized vision of a "perfect daughter." Women leaders are frequently asked pointed questions:<br>
                                        • Are we too assertive or too soft?<br>
                                        • Are we putting career ahead of family?<br>
                                        • Can we really "have it all"?<br>
                                        The truth? There is no one definition of a perfect daughter—or a perfect leader. Real success is in creating our own criteria and celebrating our uniqueness.
                                        <br><br>
                                        <strong>Redefining Perfection</strong><br>
                                        In order to really succeed, we need to shift our focus on redefining these ideals. Here's how:<br>
                                        • Be Authentic: Leadership is not about being perfect; it's about authenticity, grit, and motivating others through self-awareness.<br>
                                        </span>
                                        <span class="long-text" style="display: none;">• Set Boundaries: It's fine to say no, prioritize well-being, and ask for help when needed.<br>
                                        • Define Success on Your Terms: No matter where you work or live, success must align with personal fulfilment, not outside expectations.
                                        <br><br>
                                        <strong>Paving the Way Forward</strong><br>
                                        To be a role model is not to be perfect—it's to demonstrate strength, to be resilient, and to be ourselves. When we redefine what it means to be a "perfect daughter" and a leader, we open up space for future generations to walk the path with confidence and authenticity.
                                        <br><br>
                                        So, how have you balanced personal and professional expectations in your journey?
                                        </span>
                                    </p>
                                    <button class="read-more text-primary hover:text-primary-dark transition-colors flex items-center gap-1 animated-underline">
                                        Read More
                                        <i class="ri-arrow-right-line"></i>
                                    </button>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

